This report presents the results of the Transportation Impact Analysis (TIA) prepared for the proposed
single family residential development located at 36120 Ruschin Drive in Newark, California. Currently, the
project site contains a school, which is no longer in use. The project would develop a new residential
subdivision of 85 lots ranging in size from 2,200 square feet to 4,950 square feet. The project would
construct a new looped street to provide access to the project site. The new street would connect to the
intersection of Rosewood Drive/Ruschin Drive and create a new intersection with Ruschin Drive
approximately 200 feet south of McDonald Avenue.
This study was conducted for the purpose of identifying potential traffic impacts related to the proposed
development. The impacts of the project were evaluated following the standards and methodologies set
forth by the City of Newark. The study determined the traffic impacts of the project on five signalized
intersections five unsignalized intersections in the vicinity of the project site during the weekday AM and
Based on the ITE trip generation rates, the proposed project would generate a total of 809 daily trips, with
64 trips occurring during the AM peak hour and 85 trips occurring during the PM peak hour period.
The results of the intersection level of service analysis shows that, measured against the City of Newark
level of service impact criteria, none of the signalized study intersections would be significantly impacted
The unsignalized intersection of Newark Boulevard/Ruschin Drive-Brittany Avenue would operate with
unacceptable delays on the minor street approaches under cumulative conditions. Although this
intersection did not meet the peak hour volume warrant, the City should periodically monitor the traffic
operations at this intersection to see if a traffic signal should be installed at this location. It is also noted
that alternative routes are available for vehicles on Britanny Drive and Ruschin Drive to access Newark
Boulevard. Vehicles turning left from Brittany Drive onto northbound Newark Boulevard could alternatively
use the signalized intersection of Cedar Boulevard/Newark Boulevard and vehicles turning left from
Ruschin Drive onto southbound Newark Boulevard could alternatively use the signalized intersection of
Lafayette Avenue/Newark Boulevard to access Newark Boulevard.
The project would not have an adverse effect on existing transit, bicycle or pedestrian facilities in the study
area. Site access and on-site circulation would be adequate.

This report presents the results of the Transportation Impact Analysis (TIA) prepared for the proposed
single family residential development located at 36120 Ruschin Drive in Newark, California. Currently, the
project site contains a school, which is no longer in use. The project would develop a new residential
subdivision of 85 lots ranging in size from 2,200 square feet to 4,950 square feet. The project would
construct a new looped street to provide access to the project site. The new street would connect to the
intersection of Rosewood Drive/Ruschin Drive and create a new intersection with Ruschin Drive
approximately 200 feet south of McDonald Avenue. Figure 1 shows the study area and project site
This study was conducted for the purpose of identifying potential traffic impacts related to the proposed
development. The impacts of the project were evaluated following the standards and methodologies set
forth by the City of Newark. The study determined the traffic impacts of the project on five signalized
intersections and five unsignalized intersections in the vicinity of the project site during the weekday AM
and PM peak periods of traffic. The study intersections are identified below and shown on Figure 1.
Traffic conditions at the study intersections were analyzed for the weekday AM and PM peak hours of
adjacent street traffic. The AM peak hour of adjacent street traffic is generally between 7:00 and 9:00 AM,
and the PM peak hour of adjacent street traffic is typically between 4:00 and 6:00 PM. It is during these
periods on an average weekday that the most congested traffic conditions occur.
Traffic conditions were evaluated for the following scenarios:
Existing Conditions. Existing traffic volumes at all intersections were obtained from
manual turning-movement counts conducted in May 2014 except for the intersection of
Newark Boulevard and Ruschin Drive. AM and PM peak hour traffic volumes at this
intersection were obtained from the detailed signal warrant analysis memorandum
prepared by Omni-Means in September 2013. The counts are included in Appendix A
and the detailed signal warrant analysis memorandum is included in Appendix B.
Existing Plus Project Conditions. Existing plus project peak hour traffic volumes were
estimated by adding to existing traffic volumes the additional traffic generated by the
project. Existing plus project conditions were evaluated relative to existing conditions in
order to determine the effects the project would have on existing traffic conditions.
Background Conditions. Background traffic volumes were estimated by adding to
existing peak hour volumes the projected volumes from approved but not yet completed
developments. The added traffic from approved but not yet completed developments
was estimated from the list of approved projects in the City of Newark and the City of
Fremont provided by the City of Newark.
Background Plus Project Conditions. Projected near-term peak hour traffic volumes with
the project were estimated by adding to background traffic volumes the additional traffic
generated by the project. Background plus project conditions were evaluated relative to
background conditions in order to determine potential project impacts according to the
City of Newark Level of Service Policy.
Cumulative Conditions. Cumulative conditions are represented by traffic conditions that
would occur in Year 2035. Cumulative traffic volumes were obtained from the proposed

i.b: Analysis Methodologies and Level of Service Standards

page.text: Traffic conditions at the study intersections were evaluated using level of service (LOS). Level of Service
is a qualitative description of operating conditions ranging from LOS A, or free-flow conditions with little or
no delay, to LOS F, or jammed conditions with excessive delays. The analysis methods are described
Intersections in Newark have a LOS standard of D. An intersection operating at LOS D would typically
have some noticeable level of congestion and maybe include longer delays resulting from some
combination of unfavorable signal progression, long cycle lengths, or high volume-to-capacity ratios. Also
typical of intersections operating at LOS D is that many vehicles stop and individual cycle failures may be
noticeable. The source for this LOS standard is the Newark General Plan Tune Up Traffic Study
prepared by Hexagon Transportation Consultants in June 2013. The level of service methodology used
for this study is TRAFFIX, which is based on the 2000 Highway Capacity Manual (HCM) method for
signalized intersections. TRAFFIX evaluates signalized intersection operations on the basis of average
control delay time for all vehicles at the intersection. The correlation between average delay and level of

Level of service for the unsignalized intersections was determined using TRAFFIX based on the 2000
Highway Capacity Manual (HCM) methodology. For the purpose of this study, the level of service
reported is based on the average delay at the unsignalized intersections. The correlation between
average delay and level of service is shown in Table 2.
The City of Newark does not have formal criteria to apply to unsignalized intersections. This is common
for many jurisdictions because signalized intersections typically limit the overall capacity of a roadway.
The analysis of unsignalized intersections is typically evaluated by considering overall level of service,
movement delay, availability of alternate routes, intersection spacing, and an analysis of traffic signal

The level of service analysis at unsignalized intersections is supplemented with an assessment of the
need for signalization of the intersection. This assessment is made on the basis of signal warrant criteria
adopted by Caltrans. For this study, the need for signalization is assessed on the basis of the peak-hour
traffic signal warrant, Warrant #3 described in the 2006 California Manual on Uniform Traffic Control
Devices (CAMUTCD). This method provides an indication of whether traffic conditions and peak-hour
traffic levels are, or would be, sufficient to justify installation of a traffic signal.
The decision to install a traffic signal should not be based purely on the warrants alone. Instead, the
installation of a signal should be considered and further analysis performed when one or more of the
warrants are met. Additionally, engineering judgment is exercised on a case-by-case basis to evaluate
the effect a traffic signal will have on certain types of accidents and traffic conditions at the subject
intersection as well as at adjacent intersections.

Traffic conditions were observed in the field to identify existing operational deficiencies and to confirm the
accuracy of calculated levels of service. The purpose of this effort was (1) to identify any existing traffic
problems that may not be directly related to level of service, and (2) to identify any locations where the
level of service analysis does not accurately reflect actual existing traffic conditions.
AM and PM field observations revealed that overall the study intersections operate well, and the level of
service calculations accurately reflect existing conditions. However, field observations revealed that some
minor operational problems currently occur that may not be reflected in the intersection level of service
Cedar Boulevard and Lafayette Avenue – In the AM peak hour, the Cedar Boulevard/ Lafayette Avenue
intersection experienced long queues for the northbound and southbound through movements. Due to
synchronization in the northbound direction with Edgewater Drive, the northbound and southbound
queues rarely interfered with either intersection on Lafayette Avenue. Northbound and southbound traffic
volumes were able to clear the intersection in a single signal cycle. Occasionally, during the PM peak
hour, traffic would back up from Cedar Blvd/ Edgewater Dr. to Cedar Blvd/ Lafayette Ave due to the short
spacing between the two intersections. However, this occurred only briefly and the through vehicles
cleared the intersection in one signal cycle.
Cedar Boulevard and Thornton Avenue – In the AM peak hour, the Cedar Boulevard/ Thornton Avenue
intersection experienced lengthy queues for westbound through and the left turn lanes as well as
northbound through and left turn lanes. This is due to the close proximity to both SR 84 and I-880
freeways. The westbound left-turn queue spilled out of the turn pocket into the adjacent through lane.
However, this occurred only briefly and the left-turning vehicles cleared the intersection in one signal
cycle. The southbound left-turn pocket was frequently blocked by queues in the adjacent through lane on
southbound Cedar Boulevard, but all through traffic cleared the intersection in a single signal cycle due to
adequate green times. During the PM peak hour, this intersection experienced lengthy queues for
eastbound through and right turn movements and southbound left and through movements. The
westbound left-turn pocket was frequently blocked by queues in the adjacent through lane, which caused
westbound left-turning vehicles to wait two signal cycles to clear the intersection. The southbound left-turn
queue spilled out of the turn pocket into the adjacent through lane. However, due to long green times, all
left-turning vehicles cleared the intersection in one signal cycle. The northbound right turn lane and
eastbound left turn lane were also blocked by adjacent through lanes but all vehicles cleared the
intersection in one of their respective signal cycles.
Newark Boulevard and Jarvis Avenue – In the AM peak hour, the southbound left-turn pocket was
occasionally blocked by queues in the adjacent through lane on southbound Newark Boulevard, but all
through traffic cleared the intersection in one signal cycle. The northbound left-turn pocket was also
occasionally blocked by queues in the adjacent through lane on northbound Newark Boulevard. All
through traffic cleared the intersection in one signal cycle. During the PM peak hour, this intersection
experienced long queues for the southbound through movement. Traffic occasionally spilled back into the
Newark Blvd/SR 84 Eastbound Ramps intersection but cleared quickly once green time was give to the
southbound traffic. Vehicles generally cleared the intersection in one signal cycle. The southbound left-
turn pocket was frequently blocked by queues in the adjacent through lane on southbound Newark
Boulevard during the peak hour. Therefore, southbound left turns had to wait two cycles to clear the
intersection since there was no access to the left-turn pocket.
Newark Boulevard and Cedar Boulevard – In the PM peak hour, the southbound left-turn queue spilled
out of the turn pocket into the adjacent through lane. However, this occurred only briefly and the left-
turning vehicles cleared the intersection in one signal cycle.
Newark Boulevard and Ruschin Dr./ Brittany Ave. – During the AM peak hour, vehicles approaching
Newark Boulevard from Ruschin Drive or Brittany Avenue were able to locate sufficient gaps in traffic to
make left turns onto either southbound or northbound Newark Blvd. However, when northbound vehicles
were given green time at the Newark Blvd/ Lafayette Ave intersection, vehicles would have to wait
approximately 10 seconds to make a left or right turn safely onto Newark Blvd. In the PM peak hour,
vehicles again were able to find sufficient gaps in traffic to make left or right turns onto northbound or
southbound Newark Blvd. Vehicles approaching from Brittany Avenue would, however, have to wait
approximately 20 seconds for southbound traffic to clear when green time was given to this movement at
the Newark Blvd/ Cedar Boulevard intersection.
This chapter describes existing plus project traffic conditions, including the method by which project traffic
is estimated. Existing plus project traffic conditions could potentially occur if the project were to be
occupied prior to the other approved projects in the area. It is unlikely that this traffic condition would
occur, since other approved projects expected to add traffic to the study area would likely be built and
occupied during the time the project is going through the development review process.

text.b: Transportation Network Under Existing Plus Project Conditions

page.text: It is assumed in this analysis that the transportation network under existing plus project conditions would
be the same as the existing transportation network.
The magnitude of traffic produced by a new development and the locations where that traffic would
appear are estimated using a three-step process: (1) trip generation, (2) trip distribution, and (3) trip
assignment. In determining project trip generation, the magnitude of traffic entering and exiting the site is
estimated for the AM and PM peak hours. As part of the project trip distribution, an estimate is made of
the directions to and from which the project trips would travel. In the project trip assignment, the project
trips are assigned to specific streets. These procedures are described further in the following sections.
Through empirical research, data have been collected that quantify the amount of traffic produced by
common land uses. Thus, for the most common land uses there are standard trip generation rates that
can be applied to help predict the future traffic increases that would result from a new development. The
magnitude of traffic added to the roadway system by a particular development is estimated by multiplying
the applicable trip generation rates by the size of the development. Standard trip generation rates
published in the Institute of Transportation Engineers (ITE) manual entitled Trip Generation, Ninth Edition
The ITE rates are based on numerous counts of existing development of the same land use type. For the
residential component of the project, the rates for Single Family Detached Housing (ITE land use code
210) were used. No trip credits were taken because the existing school on site is not under operation.
Based on the ITE trip generation rates, the proposed project would generate a total of 809 daily trips, with
64 trips occurring during the AM peak hour and 85 trips occurring during the PM peak hour period. Table
4 shows the project trip generation estimates.

page.text: The project is said to create a significant adverse impact on traffic conditions at a signalized intersection
in the City of Newark if for either peak hour:
1. The level of service at the intersection degrades from an acceptable LOS under no project
conditions to an unacceptable LOS under project conditions, or
2. The level of service at the intersection is an unacceptable LOS under no project conditions and
the addition of project trips causes the average delay at the intersection to increase by four (4) or
A significant impact by the City of Newark standards is said to be satisfactorily mitigated when measures
are implemented that would restore intersection level of service to no project conditions or better.
The City of Newark does not have formal criteria to apply to unsignalized intersections. This is common
for many jurisdictions because signalized intersections typically limit the overall capacity of a roadway.

The analysis of intersection level of service was supplemented with an analysis of left-turn pocket storage
and vehicle queuing for intersections where the project would add a notable number of left turns. For the
purpose of this analysis, 5 or more peak hour vehicle trips were considered a noteworthy number of left
turns. Accordingly, not all of the study intersections were evaluated for left-turn vehicle queues. The
operations analysis is based on vehicle queuing for high demand turning movements at intersections.
Vehicle queues were estimated using a Poisson probability distribution, which estimates the probability of
“n” vehicles for a vehicle movement using the following formula:
P (x=n) = probability of “n” vehicles in queue per lane
n = number of vehicles in the queue per lane
Average # of vehicles in the queue per lane (vehicles per hr per lane/signal cycles per hr)
The basis of the analysis is as follows: (1) the Poisson probability distribution is used to estimate the 95
percentile maximum number of queued vehicles per signal cycle for a particular movement; (2) the
estimated maximum number of vehicles in the queue is translated into a queue length, assuming 25 feet
per vehicle; and (3) the maximum queue length is compared to the existing or planned available storage
capacity for the movement. This analysis thus provides a basis for estimating future left-turn storage

The site access and circulation evaluation is based on the February 9. 2014 site plan shown on Figure
11. On-site vehicular circulation was reviewed in accordance with generally accepted traffic engineering
Access to the project site will be provided via two access points on Ruschin Drive. The project will
construct a new looped street through the subdivision. The new street would connect to the intersection of
Rosewood Drive/Ruschin Drive and create a new intersection with Ruschin Drive approximately 200 feet
south of McDonald Avenue. Full access will be provided at both access points on Ruschin Drive.
Providing the appropriate sight distance reduces the likelihood of a collision at a driveway or intersection,
and provides drivers with the ability to exit a driveway or locate sufficient gaps in traffic. Sight distance
generally should be provided in accordance with Caltrans standards. The minimum acceptable sight
distance is often considered the Caltrans stopping sight distance. Sight distance requirements vary
depending on the roadway speeds. For driveways on Ruschin Drive, which likely to have a speed limit of
30 mph, the Caltrans stopping sight distance is 260 feet (based on a design speed of 40 mph). Thus, a
driver must be able to see 260 feet down Ruschin Drive in order to stop and avoid a collision. Adequate
sight distance should be provided at both project driveways. Both project driveways on Ruschin Drive
should be free and clear of obstructions and provide good sight distance.
Both the driveways on Ruschin Drive are expected to operate well with the proposed project. Due to low
traffic volumes on Ruschin Drive, the project outbound vehicles are likely to easily find gaps in the
uncontrolled traffic flow on Ruschin Drive.

text.b: Intersection Levels of Service Under Cumulative Conditions

page.text: The results of the intersection level of service analysis under cumulative conditions show that, measured
against the City of Newark level of service standards, all of the signalized study intersections would
operate at an acceptable level of service during both the AM and PM peak hours of traffic (see Table 10).
All unsignalized intersections would continue to operate at LOS C for the worst approach on the minor
street except for the intersection of Newark Boulevard and Ruschin Drive. The intersection of Newark
Boulevard and Ruschin Drive is expected to operate with long unacceptable delays on the minor street
approaches of Brittany Avenue and Ruschin Drive during both the AM and PM peak hour durations under
cumulative conditions without and with the proposed project. With the increase in traffic volumes on
Newark Boulevard, it would be harder for vehicles on the stop controlled approaches of Britanny Drive
and Ruschin Drive to find gaps in the traffic flow on Newark Boulevard. However, this intersection would
not meet the peak hour signal warrant during both the AM and PM peak hour durations under cumulative
conditions without and with the project. As discussed earlier, the City recently completed a detailed signal
warrant analysis that looked at eight of the nine signal warrants in the CAMUTCD and found that this
intersection did not fully meet any one of the eight signal volume warrants. It is recommended that the
City periodically monitor the traffic operations at this intersection to see if a traffic signal should be
installed at this location. It is also noted that alternative routes are available for vehicles on Britanny Drive
and Ruschin Drive to access Newark Boulevard. Vehicles turning left from Brittany Drive onto northbound
Newark Boulevard could alternatively use the signalized intersection of Cedar Boulevard/Newark
Boulevard and vehicles turning left from Ruschin Drive onto southbound Newark Boulevard could
alternatively use the signalized intersection of Lafayette Avenue/Newark Boulevard to access Newark
